# Basics of the SmolNet

The small internet, or SmolNet, really just refers to any slice of internet that is built around intentionally simplified experiences, without flash, and without privacy violations. This means that, in actuality, SmolNet can include HTML sites, served over HTTP(S)... but in practice, many (most?) use the term to refer specifically to corners of the internet where HTTP/HTML are avoided altogether, and in particular to corners where two protocols in particular are used in their place.

The two SmolNet protocols in question are Gopher, and Gemini. Gemini's name has run into a bit of misfortune, as Google has chosen to use the same name for their AI agent technology. In order to avoid confusion, I've tried to specifically refer to Gemini as "the Gemini protocol" wherever practical.

It's helpful to understand just a little bit about the protocols, and their related history, in order to set what your expectations should be when surfing the SmolNet, and especially to help explain why certain convenient features are missing, that you might have come to expect from years of surfing the Web.

